<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="323" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,258,1507]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1194,1219]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[332,532,1195,1219]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[332,532,1195,1219]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Campsurus janae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[543,637,1194,1219]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[543,637,1194,1219]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is known from male adults only. It can be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1868" box="[276,403,1231,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[276,403,1231,1254]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Campsurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: 1) posterior margin of male abdominal sternum IX truncated (
<figureCitation box="[1187,1287,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 76" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[265,1305,209,1801]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[260,1326,193,1805]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 76. Male adults. Campsurus zunigae sp. nov.: 68, genitalia of imago, v. v.; 69, genitalia of subimago, l. v.; 70, detail of penes of imago, l. v. Campsurus pereirae sp. nov., imago: 71, genitalia, v. v.; 72, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 73, detail of penes, v. v.; 74, genitalia, l. v. (forceps omitted). Campsurus janae sp. nov., imago: 75, genitalia, v. v.: 76, detail of penes, l. v." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838452/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Figs. 75</figureCitation>
); 2) pedestal almost touching each other medially, strongly elongated, parastylus short, broad and rounded apically, inner corner strongly projected (
<figureCitation box="[379,468,1302,1327]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 76" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[265,1305,209,1801]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[260,1326,193,1805]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 76. Male adults. Campsurus zunigae sp. nov.: 68, genitalia of imago, v. v.; 69, genitalia of subimago, l. v.; 70, detail of penes of imago, l. v. Campsurus pereirae sp. nov., imago: 71, genitalia, v. v.; 72, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 73, detail of penes, v. v.; 74, genitalia, l. v. (forceps omitted). Campsurus janae sp. nov., imago: 75, genitalia, v. v.: 76, detail of penes, l. v." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838452/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Fig. 75</figureCitation>
); 3) base of main lobe of penes strongly expanded laterodorsally (
<figureCitation box="[1259,1347,1302,1327]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 76" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1825,1848]" captionTargetBox="[265,1305,209,1801]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[260,1326,193,1805]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 76. Male adults. Campsurus zunigae sp. nov.: 68, genitalia of imago, v. v.; 69, genitalia of subimago, l. v.; 70, detail of penes of imago, l. v. Campsurus pereirae sp. nov., imago: 71, genitalia, v. v.; 72, detail of pedestal, v. v.; 73, detail of penes, v. v.; 74, genitalia, l. v. (forceps omitted). Campsurus janae sp. nov., imago: 75, genitalia, v. v.: 76, detail of penes, l. v." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838452/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Fig. 76</figureCitation>
), penes narrowing abruptly on apical half, main lobe of penes apically pointed and curved ventrally; secondary membranous lobe relatively short and cylindrical; 4) small size (length of male fore wings 
<quantity box="[1168,1258,1374,1399]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" unit="mm" value="6.5">6.5 mm</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="323" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,258,1507]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1410,1435]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[339,535,1411,1435]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[339,535,1411,1435]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Campsurus janae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[542,632,1410,1435]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[542,632,1410,1435]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[778,904,1411,1435]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pereirae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[778,904,1411,1435]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">C. pereirae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[911,1001,1410,1435]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[911,1001,1410,1435]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but the extremely large and elongated pedestal of 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[279,373,1447,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[279,373,1447,1470]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">C. janae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[380,469,1446,1471]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[380,469,1446,1471]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
easily differentiates it. 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[730,926,1447,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="janae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[730,926,1447,1470]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">Campsurus janae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[933,1022,1446,1471]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[933,1022,1446,1471]" pageId="22" pageNumber="323">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is described as a pharate male imago (still inside the subimaginal cuticle), but the characteristic genitalia are sclerotized and in their final configuration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
